A free trade pact between the EU and four South American countries was thrown further into doubt on Wednesday after Austria's parliament rejected the agreement. Nearly all parties in the Austrian parliament's EU subcommittee voted against the EU-Mercosur free trade agreement. Read more: EU-Mercosur free trade deal — What you need to know The government is obliged to follow the decision of the subcommittee at the EU level, where according to rules all 28 member states and their parliaments must agree to trade deals. Mercosur is a South America free trade zone comprising Brazil, Uruguay, Paraguay and Argentina. Send  Facebook   Twitter   google+   Whatsapp   Tumblr   linkedin   stumble   Digg   reddit   Newsvine Permalink https://p.dw.com/p/3M85o The trade agreement reached last June after almost a decade of negotiations was already put into doubt due to concerns over fires in the Amazon rainforest and the politics of Brazilian President Jair Bolsonaro. France, Ireland and Luxembourg had already suggested the trade deal may be put on hold over environmental concerns in the Amazon. Send  Facebook   Twitter   google+   Whatsapp   Tumblr   linkedin   stumble   Digg   reddit   Newsvine Permalink https://p.dw.com/p/3LbX1 cw/se (dpa, Reuters) Each evening at 1830 UTC, DW's editors send out a selection of the day's hard news and quality feature journalism. You can sign up to receive it directly here. 